comment_data.body:
@lu-zero That's a nice link--and I'll be sure to keep it around--but it still seems incomplete.  Unfortunately, we can't rely just on you to help with the build.  As dependencies pop up, developers want to be able to add them when they need them, and so it means others needs to modify the build as well.  That's where the pain comes in. :-(

I'm not saying CMake is perfect--it is not, and I've not met any build tool that is.  CMake has certainly got its share of issues--many of which I agree with you on.  But, as a developer, CMake is far easier to wrap my head around.  And, it allows me to use tools--like Ninja--who have much better build times than make.

In the end it's about a trade-off: more pain on the packaging front, or more pain on the development front.  NeoVim is not the first project to use CMake, so I feel it's best to optimize for the latter (sorry!).  And at the end of the day, you have to use either tool smartly.  Perhaps you can help us to make your life easier by making sure we do that with CMake.
